There are matters of scale and leverage, cross-sectional area of the muscles that move the jawbone, the location where she is exerting pressure, and so on. I am inclined to think that it looks a bit odd, because foxes IRL are small omnivores that rarely hunt anything bigger than mice, squirrels, and birds, and kind of delicate compared to most other canids. On the other hand she is some kind of forest goddess, so she is allowed to have superpowers if it serves the plot.

IRL the canid with the strongest bite force is a dog, a very large Turkish mastiff breed called the Kangol. They were bred for this, to be hunting and guard dogs. Their bite force is about 60% of what an adult male polar bear can produce, supposedly.

And when I look for information online about questions like "how much pressure to break a human bone" and "can animal X break bones with its jaws" I get a lot of contradictory numbers and a lot of "well acktchewally" articles. I do not think a human-size fox would have extremely powerful jaws. The muscles for that attach atop the head. An anthro fox with a brain the size of a human brain would have either jaw muscles comparable to a human's, and a longer jaw with less leverage up front for lower force, or a large and bulbous head with great bundles of muscle attached to a massive bony crest going over the top of the skull from front to back.

But Lisa is a fox goddess, or demoness, or something, so she can do that if the writer wants her to, I guess.
